and":"英國諾圖波藍德阿恩維克","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"英國諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"法國諾爾-帕-德-卡拉斯","lifeSummary":"Richard Tison是Gilbert de Tesson Lord of Alnwick和Beatrix of Normandy的兒子，出生在英國諾圖波藍德阿恩維克。他於1135年與Tyson在英國諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾結婚。他們至少是2個兒子的父母。他去世於1166年之前在英國諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾。"},"zh-hans":{"–before 1166":"–1166年之前","1050–1096":"1050年–1096年","–1166":"–1166年","1115–Female":"1115年–殁","1135–1177":"1135年–1177年","1135–1178":"1135年–1178年","1035–1066":"1035年–1066年","1038–1074":"1038年–1074年","before 1166":"1166年之前","1066":"1066年","1086":"1086年","1074":"1074年","1096":"1096年","1050":"1050年","1106":"1106年","1038":"1038年","1115":"1115年","1135":"1135年","1035":"1035年","1178":"1178年","1177":"1177年","1166":"1166年","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"英国諾圖波藍德阿恩維克","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"英国諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"法国諾爾-帕-德-卡拉斯","lifeSummary":"Richard Tison是Gilbert de Tesson Lord of Alnwick和Beatrix of Normandy的儿子，出生在英国諾圖波藍德阿恩維克。他于1135年与Tyson在英国諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他去世于1166年之前在英国諾圖波藍德希爾波特爾。"},"hr":{"–before 1166":"–prije 1166.","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–preminula","1135–1177":"1135.–1177","1135–1178":"1135.–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066.","1038–1074":"1038–1074.","before 1166":"prije 1166.","1066":"1066.","1086":"1086","1074":"1074.","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135.","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Francuska"},"cs":{"–before 1166":"–před 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Zesnulá","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"před 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, Anglie","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, Anglie","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Francie"},"da":{"–before 1166":"–før 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Afdød","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"før 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrig"},"nl":{"–before 1166":"–vóór 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Overleden","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"vóór 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk"},"en":{"–before 1166":"–before 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"before 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tison","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>tison</i> ‘piece of wood’ and ‘firebrand’, in the latter sense perhaps denoting someone with a fiery temperament.","French (Nord and Pas-de-Calais): ethnic name from a derivative of Old French <i>teis</i> ‘German, Flemish’, from ancient Germanic <i>theod</i> ‘people’. Compare   Teson   and   Tesson  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Theissen   or   Theisen  . Compare   Tyson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tesson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Arnaud, Elmire, Gaston, Pierre.","French (mainly Vendée and Normandy): from <i>tesson</i>, a dialect word meaning ‘badger’, applied as a nickname for someone thought to resemble the animal in some way.","Altered form of French   Tison  . Compare   Teson  ."]},{"name":"Teson","meanings":["Altered form of French   Tison  . Compare   Tesson  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":20,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":40,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":50,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":60,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Tison was born in Alnwick, Northumberland, England as the son of Gilbert de Tesson Lord of Alnwick and Beatrix of Normandy. He married Tyson in 1135, in Shilbottle, Northumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1166, in Shilbottle, Northumberland, England."},"et":{"–before 1166":"–enne 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"enne 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–before 1166":"–ennen vuotta 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166":"–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1135–1178":"1135–1178","1035–1066":"1035–1066","1038–1074":"1038–1074","before 1166":"ennen vuotta 1166","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1035":"1035","1178":"1178","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shilbottle, Northumberland, England":"Shilbottle, Northumberland, England","Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska"},"fr":{"–before 1166":"–avant 1166","1050–1096":"1050–1096","–1166"